(1)S
90 108 :M
f1_14 sf
-.5(1.)A
126 108 :M
-.11(Introduction)A
90 138 :M
f0_10 sf
-.004(The object recognition problem is essentially this: given some knowledge of how certain objects may)A
90 158 :M
-.003(appear, plus an image of a scene possibly containing those objects, report which objects are present in the)A
90 178 :M
-.005(scene and where. This general definition admits many specific variations, not all of which will be consid-)A
90 198 :M
-.045(ered here.)A
108 218 :M
(\245)S
121 218 :M
-.002(Approaches differ according to what sort of knowledge they employ. We will be concerned with)A
121 238 :M
f2_10 sf
-.011(model-based)A
f0_10 sf
-.01( object recognition, in which the knowledge of an object\325s appearance is provided by)A
121 258 :M
-.009(an explicit model of its shape. We won\325t be considering some other types of knowledge that may be)A
121 278 :M
-.003(used to recognize an object, such as knowledge of the context in which it may be found \(Strat and)A
121 298 :M
-.003(Fischler 1991\) or the function for which it may serve \(Stark and Bowyer 1991\).)A
108 318 :M
(\245)S
121 318 :M
-.002(Approaches differ according to what restrictions they place on the form of the objects recognized.)A
121 338 :M
-.008(The objects may be two-dimensional\321like symbols printed on traffic signs\321or fully three-dimen-)A
121 358 :M
-.001(sional. Their shape may be restricted to a simple form\321such as the class of polyhedra\321or allowed)A
121 378 :M
-.009(to be more complex. They may be entirely rigid, composed of a few parts that can move rigidly)A
121 398 :M
-.001(with respect to each other \(\322articulate\323\), or capable of deforming throughout a whole range of)A
121 418 :M
-.026(shapes.)A
108 438 :M
(\245)S
121 438 :M
-.005(Approaches differ according to the kind of image they are designed for. Some find objects in an)A
121 458 :M
-.001(intensity image, and others, in a range image or a combination of range and intensity images.)A
121 478 :M
-.01(Recognizing a 3D object in an intensity image of an unrestricted scene is, in many respects, the)A
121 498 :M
-.007(most difficult form of the problem. It requires dealing with the loss of depth information due to)A
121 518 :M
(projection, with the possibility that objects may occlude each other, and with the fact that image)S
121 538 :M
-.007(intensity is only indirectly related to object shape.)A
90 568 :M
-.007(Recognition is accomplished by finding a correspondence between certain features of the image and com-)A
90 588 :M
-.007(parable features of the model. The two most important issues that a method must address are what consti)A
509 588 :M
(-)S
90 608 :M
-.004(tutes a feature, and how is the correspondence found between image features and model features. Some)A
90 628 :M
-.043(methods use )A
f2_10 sf
-.051(global)A
168 628 :M
f0_10 sf
-.001( features, which summarize information about the entire visible portion of an object.)A
90 648 :M
-.001(Examples of such features are area, perimeter length, compactness, and Euler number. Global feature)A
90 668 :M
-.003(methods are popular for those applications where lighting can be precisely controlled and occlusion does)A
90 688 :M
-.007(not occur, but because they presuppose perfect segmentation of objects from their background and from)A
endp
