-.003(method performs. Most researchers have been concerned with the following criteria, as summarized by)A
90 178 :M
-.066(Grimson \(1990\):)A
139 199 :M
f2_10 sf
-.191(scope)A
180 199 :M
f0_10 sf
-.012(What kinds of objects can be recognized, and in what kinds of scenes?)A
119 219 :M
f2_10 sf
-.086(robustness)A
180 219 :M
f0_10 sf
-.003(Does the method tolerate reasonable amounts of noise and occlusion in the scene,)A
180 234 :M
-.013(and does it degrade gracefully as those tolerances are exceeded?)A
124 254 :M
f2_10 sf
-.034(efficiency)A
180 254 :M
f0_10 sf
-.003(Recognition requires that an enormous space of alternatives be considered. How)A
180 269 :M
-.013(much time and memory are required to search that space?)A
116 289 :M
f2_10 sf
-.009(correctness)A
180 289 :M
f0_10 sf
(We cannot define correctness in any absolute sense because the object recognition)S
180 304 :M
-.009(problem is too loosely defined. Nevertheless, each method is based on a particular)A
180 319 :M
-.01(definition of the problem that engenders some criteria for ranking the alternate inter)A
515 319 :M
(-)S
180 334 :M
-.004(pretations of a scene and deciding which of those interpretations to report. We can)A
180 349 :M
-.011(ask, then, does the method correctly implement the intended ranking and decision)A
180 364 :M
-.01(criteria, or, instead, does it sometimes miss an interpretation that it should have)A
180 379 :M
-.014(preferred.)A
90 408 :M
-.002(The remainder of this survey is in three parts. Chapter 2 addresses the representation of object models and)A
90 428 :M
-.004(images for the purpose of recognition. Chapter 3 addresses methods of finding suitable matches between)A
90 448 :M
(object models and images. In chapter 4 we conclude that there is still much room for improvement in the)S
90 468 :M
-.001(scope, robustness, and efficiency of object recognition methods, and we identify what we believe are the)A
90 488 :M
-.023(ways improvements will be achieved.)A
90 518 :M
-.007(There have been other surveys published on object recognition. Extensive ones by Besl and Jain \(1985\) and)A
90 538 :M
-.001(by Chin and Dyer \(1986\) are now largely out-of-date, and omit research areas of recent importance such as)A
90 558 :M
-.002(geometric invariants and alignment matching. A survey by Brady, Nandhakumar, and Aggarwal \(1989\) is)A
90 578 :M
