90 238 :M
-.008(Lowe \(1985, 1990\) first explicitly addressed the role of perceptual organization in object recognition. He)A
90 258 :M
-.002(suggested the following rationale \(somewhat simplified here\) for guiding grouping decisions. Because a)A
90 278 :M
-.002(viewpoint invariant structure projects the same pattern over a wide range of viewpoints, that pattern is more)A
90 298 :M
-.005(likely to occur in images than other patterns. Moreover, an occurrence of the pattern is more likely due to)A
90 318 :M
-.004(the presence of the 3D structure than to some accidental alignment or objects. Thus any arrangement of)A
90 338 :M
-.003(features that matches the pattern closely enough ought to be grouped. How close must the match be? Given)A
90 358 :M
-.007(a set of features, a viewpoint invariant pattern, and some assumptions about how features are distributed)A
90 378 :M
-.003(due to chance, one can estimate the probability that the features would match the pattern at least as well as)A
90 398 :M
-.004(they do due to chance alone. This is essentially the probability of the feature arrangement arising by acci-)A
90 418 :M
-.009(dent. If that probability is below some threshold, then the features are grouped.)A
90 448 :M
-.004(Except for work by Jacobs \(1989\) on grouping pairs of convex contours, there seems to have been no other)A
90 468 :M
-.006(effort like this to found grouping decisions upon first principles. Instead, it has been common practice to)A
90 488 :M
-.003(develop ad hoc criteria for deciding which sets of features should be grouped \(e.g., Bergevin and Levine)A
90 508 :M
-.009(1992; Horaud, Veillon, and Skordas 1990; Mohan and Nevatia 1992; Sarkar and Boyer 1990; Saund 1990;)A
90 528 :M
-.006(Stein and Medioni 1992a\). Researchers concerned with the problem of how to identify groups efficiently)A
90 548 :M
-.001(have produced data structures for quickly locating related features \(Sarkar and Boyer 1990; Saund 1990;)A
90 568 :M
-.001(Stein and Medioni 1992a\), parallelizable algorithms \(Mahoney 1987; McCafferty 1990\), and other process)A
90 588 :M
-.006(improvements \(Huttenlocher and Wayner 1992\). Sarkar and Boyer \(1993\) have represented the grouping)A
90 608 :M
-.003(process using a Bayes network in order to allow a control strategy more flexible than the usual bottom-up)A
90 628 :M
-.004(process. With their approach a grouping hypothesis may lead to a top-down search for additional evidence)A
90 648 :M
-.003(in the image, and hypotheses may compete with one another to resolve choices among alternate groupings.)A
endp
