-.005(Given a library of object models and some features found in an image, we want to select a model that is)A
90 138 :M
-.007(likely to match those features. In this, the indexing problem, the goal is to do much better than simply try-)A
90 158 :M
-.004(ing each model in turn. Solutions generally involve a table that is indexed either by individual features or)A
90 178 :M
-.009(by small groups of them. Each table entry indicates a model \(and perhaps viewpoint\) that could produce the)A
90 198 :M
(corresponding feature or group. Before recognition, the table entries are created for various viewpoints of)S
90 218 :M
-.009(each model by analyzing the model library, by rendering each model from a sample of viewpoints, or by)A
90 238 :M
-.007(processing a representative set of training images. During recognition, features chosen from the image are)A
90 258 :M
-.001(used to index the table, thus producing hypotheses about what objects are present in the image. Each)A
90 278 :M
-.008(hypothesis denotes a possible, partial match between model and image, which must be further tested to)A
90 298 :M
-.004(determine the full extent and quality of the match.)A
90 328 :M
-.005(Many variations of this basic scheme are possible, and several have been investigated. We might index the)A
90 348 :M
-.002(table using all features from the image \(Breuel 1990\), a randomly chosen subset of features \(Lamdan,)A
90 368 :M
-.006(Schwartz, and Wolfson 1988\), or just features that are judged particularly likely to be derived from single)A
90 388 :M
-.001(objects \(Clemens and Jacobs 1991b\). We might test every hypothesis retrieved from the table for a possible)A
90 408 :M
-.002(match \(Clemens and Jacobs 1991b\), or instead treat the hypotheses as votes, and only test those that receive)A
90 428 :M
-.004(the most votes \(Lamdan, Schwartz, and Wolfson 1988\) or some minimum number of votes \(Stein and)A
90 448 :M
-.002(Medioni 1992b\). Votes may all bear equal weight, or they may be weighted according to the size of the)A
90 468 :M
-.002(lookup feature or how well the lookup feature matches each table entry \(Beis and Lowe 1993; Rigoutsos)A
90 488 :M
-.01(and Hummel 1993; Sarachik and Grimson 1993\).)A
90 518 :M
-.008(If not all features are used to index the table, or if voting is used and only those hypotheses receiving the)A
90 538 :M
-.008(most votes are tested, then we must have some way of deciding when we have examined enough features or)A
90 558 :M
-.007(tested enough hypotheses. One approach is to estimate the probability of missing a model with each test)A
90 578 :M
-.001(and repeat testing until the cumulative probability drops below any desired error threshold \(Lamdan,)A
90 598 :M
-.033(Schwartz, and Wolfson 1988\).)A
90 628 :M
-.003(How well indexing performs depends on how well entries are distributed throughout the table. The entries)A
90 648 :M
-.005(associated with any one object should occupy a relatively small portion of the entire table, and each entry)A
90 668 :M
-.003(should refer to relatively few objects. Poor distributions occur when objects are symmetrical or when they)A
90 688 :M
-.006(share common features \(Flynn 1992\).)A
