-.009(The efficiency of a correspondence space search is significantly affected by the order in which features are)A
90 138 :M
-.001(considered for matching. At each stage of the search one would like to choose an unmatched model feature)A
90 158 :M
-.007(that is likely to be found in the image when the object is present, is relatively unique among features of the)A
90 178 :M
-.007(model, is not likely to be encountered when the object is not present, can effectively constrain other)A
90 198 :M
-.006(matches, and, according to what is already known about the object\325s pose, can be expected to lie within a)A
90 218 :M
-.027(small region of the image.)A
90 248 :M
-.001(Goad \(1983\) suggested how one might use criteria like these to choose the next model feature for each)A
90 268 :M
-.001(stage of an interpretation tree search. To measure the criteria he proposed sampling a uniform distribution)A
90 288 :M
-.005(of viewpoints, estimating the object\325s appearance from each viewpoint using a 3D model, and tallying each)A
90 308 :M
-.008(feature\325s visibility and position. The tallies would be used to rank each feature according to how likely it is)A
90 328 :M
-.005(to be visible, how accurately its position can be predicted, and how much information about the object\325s)A
90 348 :M
-.002(pose would be provided by matching it. This analysis would be used to pre-determine the entire search tree)A
90 368 :M
-.005(for a given model before any recognition attempts. Goad\325s experiments demonstrated the idea of pre-order-)A
90 388 :M
-.008(ing the search tree but they did not test his ranking criteria\321features were ordered subjectively, by hand.)A
90 408 :M
-.001(Kuno, Okamoto, and Okada \(1991\) have described a similar approach that also considers the likelihood of)A
90 428 :M
-.003(features arising accidentally, the cost of detecting them, and the degree to which they may be distorted by)A
90 448 :M
-.011(perspective. Another variation, the )A
f2_10 sf
-.012(local feature focus method)A
f0_10 sf
-.012( \(Bolles and Cain 1982\), involves analyzing)A
90 468 :M
