-.018(Verifying the match result)A
90 118 :M
f0_10 sf
-.007(The last step in the recognition process is to decide whether an optimal match found by the match search)A
90 138 :M
-.001(actually represents an instance of an object in the image. There has been relatively little research on how)A
90 158 :M
-.004(best to make this decision. Many systems simply require that some fraction of the model\325s features be)A
90 178 :M
-.005(matched, and/or that some fraction of the edges projected from the model lie near image edges \(e.g., Chen)A
90 198 :M
-.002(and Kak 1989; Gottschalk, Turney, and Mudge 1989; Lamdan, Schwartz, and Wolfson 1990\). Some also)A
90 218 :M
-.002(assess negative evidence, such as image edges that cross projected model edges at large angles \(e.g.,)A
90 238 :M
-.001(Hansen and Henderson 1989; Huttenlocher and Ullman 1990\). Match solutions are verified by testing these)A
90 258 :M
-.001(measures against empirically determined thresholds, and then ranked according to the measures to select)A
90 278 :M
-.021(the best, mutually-consistent solutions.)A
90 308 :M
-.004(Grimson, Huttenlocher, and Sarachik have developed analytic models for estimating the probability that a)A
90 328 :M
-.002(particular match may be accidental\321i.e., due to a conspiracy of random features rather than the actual)A
90 348 :M
-.006(presence of the object \(Grimson and Huttenlocher 1991; Sarachik and Grimson 1993\). Only if this probabil-)A
90 368 :M
-.007(ity is below some threshold is the match accepted. Chen and Mulgaonkar \(1992\) have used a similar analy-)A
90 388 :M
-.005(sis not only to accept or reject matches, but also to halt the match search as soon as a sufficiently reliable)A
90 408 :M
-.015(decision can be made.)A
90 438 :M
-.008(Recently, Breuel \(1993\) has suggested that verification consider not only how much of a model is matched,)A
90 458 :M
-.005(but also the spatial distribution of its unmatched parts. In a valid match, the features that remain unmatched)A
90 478 :M
-.008(do so primarily because of occluding objects that typically cover contiguous regions of the image.)A
90 498 :M
-.009(Verification, therefore, should test how well these unmatched features can be explained away by hypothe)A
511 498 :M
(-)S
90 518 :M
-.01(sizing a small number of contiguous occlusions.)A
endp
