-.099(Conclusion)A
90 138 :M
f0_10 sf
-.009(Early in this survey we listed the criteria commonly used to evaluate object recognition methods: scope,)A
90 158 :M
-.001(robustness, efficiency, and correctness. We should now ask, how well have existing methods met these)A
90 178 :M
(requirements, and what factors have contributed to the difficulties and successes in these areas?)S
90 208 :M
f2_10 sf
-.219(Scope)A
90 238 :M
f0_10 sf
-.009(Most methods are applicable only to highly restricted classes of objects, and none can cope with the full)A
90 258 :M
-.001(range of objects found in natural environments. Usually objects are required to have smooth contours and)A
90 278 :M
-.008(be rigid or articulate so that they can be readily matched against a simple, fixed model of shape. These)A
90 298 :M
-.005(restrictions may not be a problem in special situations, as in factories, but they effectively rule out recogni)A
515 298 :M
(-)S
90 318 :M
-.02(tion of most objects in most environments.)A
90 348 :M
-.004(One factor that often seems to underlie this scope restriction is a reliance on some small, fixed set of shape)A
90 368 :M
-.005(primitives for describing all objects. Invariably these primitives embody strong assumptions about objects,)A
90 388 :M
-.001(and consequently they are only suitable for representing objects that fit those assumptions. For example,)A
90 408 :M
-.001(one scheme represents an object as composed of a small number of generic parts, such as generalized)A
90 428 :M
-.004(cylinders or superquadrics. The generic parts are kept simple so that they can be segmented and identified)A
90 448 :M
-.007(in images prior to recognition; as a consequence, however, the parts are of limited representational power)A
90 468 :M
-.002(and they are unable to portray many natural objects \(the scheme also omits any representation of object)A
90 488 :M
-.008(markings\). Another scheme is to recognize objects using geometric invariants; then objects must also be)A
90 508 :M
-.007(severely restricted because there are no suitable invariants for unrestricted configurations of points.)A
90 538 :M
(It appears that a solution to the scope problem will not come from finding some small, universal set of)S
90 558 :M
-.009(features capable of representing any object. We should expect, instead, that a rather broad range of features)A
90 578 :M
-.008(will be needed. Many of these features might apply only to certain objects but, collectively, they would be)A
90 598 :M
-.006(able to generate rich descriptions of a large class of objects. Furthermore, since it would be impractical for)A
90 618 :M
-.006(any designer to try to anticipate all features that could prove useful for recognition, it will be important for)A
90 638 :M
-.008(a general purpose recognition system to be able to coin new features as needed. So far there have been only)A
90 658 :M
-.005(a few efforts to construct recognition systems capable of learning their own representations; we might hope)A
90 678 :M
-.01(to see much more effort in this area.)A
endp
