-.003(sets of objects and images, it is difficult to assess how robust these methods truly are. Trials comparing)A
90 158 :M
-.006(alternate methods under similar conditions are extremely rare. We can speculate, however, as to which)A
90 178 :M
-.001(among the current crop of ideas seem most important for achieving robustness. They appear to be the)A
90 198 :M
-.073(following:)A
108 218 :M
(\245)S
121 218 :M
f2_10 sf
-.005(Effective use of redundant information)A
f0_10 sf
-.005(. An image of an object usually contains a considerable)A
121 238 :M
-.003(amount of redundant information. In some ways, this redundancy can compensate for missing or)A
121 258 :M
-.008(inaccurate features. For example, the indexing methods reviewed in section 3.2 use this redundancy)A
121 278 :M
-.006(to identify correct interpretations even when a large proportion of features are missing or inaccu-)A
121 298 :M
-.009(rate. Another use of redundancy is in representations that span a range of scales; large-scale features)A
121 318 :M
-.002(make explicit certain information that is already implicitly available in small-scale ones, but the)A
121 338 :M
-.003(large-scale features allow objects to be easily recognized as similar even when they differ in some)A
121 358 :M
-.086(details.)A
108 378 :M
(\245)S
121 378 :M
f2_10 sf
-.009(Use of probabilistic models)A
f0_10 sf
-.009(. A simple approach assumes that an object can be modeled as a single,)A
121 398 :M
-.008(idealized form, and that any departure of its actual form from this ideal is simply \322noise\323. In prac-)A
121 418 :M
-.006(tice, however, individual objects of the same type often differ in particular ways; some features are)A
121 438 :M
-.004(not shared by all individuals and feature geometry may vary. Pencils, for example, differ greatly in)A
121 458 :M
-.009(length and in the conditions of their two ends, but in other ways they are quite similar. Probabilistic)A
121 478 :M
(models like those described in section 2.6 try to represent these kinds of variations more accurately,)S
121 498 :M
-.011(and their use should permit more reliable recognition of classes of similar objects.)A
108 518 :M
(\245)S
121 518 :M
f2_10 sf
-.032(Use of probabilistic reasoning)A
243 518 :M
f0_10 sf
-.011(. Matching methods are now often formulated in terms of some simi)A
516 518 :M
(-)S
121 538 :M
-.004(larity measure and, increasingly, that measure is based on probability theory. Probability theory)A
121 558 :M
-.002(provides a framework for integrating a probabilistic model, the observations of many noisy features,)A
121 578 :M
(and other sources of knowledge. The framework contributes to robustness by allowing appropriate)S
121 598 :M
-.014(importance to be accorded each of many information sources.)A
90 628 :M
-.006(This survey has not examined how feature detection is accomplished. Nevertheless, that is also an area)A
90 648 :M
-.005(where we should be seeking improvements to enhance the robustness of object detection. Of course, with-)A
